JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 114
IS  - 2
SP  - 629
EP  - 653
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Recently, several central banks have lost their bank supervisory responsibilities, in part because it has not been shown that supervisory authority improves the conduct of monetary policy. This paper finds that confidential bank supervisory information could help the Board staff more accurately forecast important macroeconomic variables and is used by FOMC members to guide monetary policy. These findings suggest that the complementarity between supervisory responsibilities and monetary policy should be an important consideration when evaluating the structure of the central bank.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/003355399556098
ER  - 



